# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bambangan-condiment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:bambangan-condiment/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:bambangan-condiment/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:bambangan-condiment/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] The names mean 'garlic and oil' in Catalan and Provençal.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] It is found in the cuisines of southeastern France (Provence, Languedoc, Roussillon) and eastern Spain (traditionally Catalonia and to a lesser extent the Valencian Community, the Balearic Islands, Murcia, and eastern Andalusia).
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Some versions of the sauce are closer to a garlic mayonnaise, incorporating egg yolks and lemon juice, while other versions omit egg yolk and contain more garlic.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] The garlic gives the sauce a pastier texture, making it more laborious to produce as the emulsion is harder to stabilise.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] There are many variations, such as adding lemon juice or other seasonings.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] In Malta, arjoli or ajjoli is quite different; it is made with galletti (a type of cracker), tomato, onion, garlic, and herbs.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Like mayonnaise, aioli is an emulsion or suspension of small globules of oil and oil-soluble compounds in water and water-soluble compounds.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Many older recipes do not include egg, but nowadays, egg or egg yolk is the usual emulsifier.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Since about 1990, it has become common in the United States to call all flavored mayonnaises *aioli*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Purists insist that true aioli must contain garlic and no other seasoning (except salt).
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] In the form *aioli*, the word is a compound of Provençal *ai* 'garlic' and *oli* 'oil'.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] The English spelling comes from the French *aïoli*, which is an adaptation of an Occitan term.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] The spelling in Occitan may be *alhòli*, following the classical norm, or *aiòli*, following the Mistralian norm.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] In Catalan it is spelled *allioli* (pronounced [ˌaʎiˈɔli]).
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] The most common term in Spanish is *alioli*, an adaptation from Catalan, although there are alternative Spanish terms such as *ajoaceite*, *ajiaceite*, *ajolio* or *ajaceite*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] It is also spelled *alioli* in Galician.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Garlic is crushed in a mortar and pestle and emulsified with salt and olive oil.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Today, aioli is often made in a food processor or blender, but some traditionalists object that this does not give the same result.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] In Occitan cuisine, *aioli* is typically served with seafood, fish soup, and croutons.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] An example is a dish called *merluça amb alhòli*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] In the Occitan Alps it is served with potatoes boiled with salt and bay laurel.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] This dish is often served during the festivities on the feast days of the patron saint of Provençal villages and towns.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] It is traditional to serve it with snails for Christmas Eve and with cod on Ash Wednesday.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Aïoli is so strongly associated with Provence that when the poet Frédéric Mistral started a regionalist Provençal-language newspaper in 1891, he called it *L'Aiòli*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] The Provençal cuisine fish soup bourride is generally served with *aioli*.
[src:bambangan-condiment/aioli] Other commonly used vegetables are beets, fennel, celery, zucchini, cauliflower, chickpeas, and raw tomatoes.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] Traditionally, an ice shaving machine is used to churn out the shaved ice used in the dessert, originally hand cranked but now more often motorised.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] Many Southeast Asian coffee shops, hawker centres and food courts sell this dessert.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] Early versions of ais kacang was first known to have been prepared around the time before and after the First World War, where the costs of ice manufacturing was becoming more affordable.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] An earlier variant of the Singaporean dish was described as green, made from shaved ice, paired with syrups, *soaked seeds* and seaweed jelly and was sold mainly by street vendors.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] The dish underwent many different alterations and variants throughout the history of Singapore, where during the 1920s, one version of it was described as shaved ice topped with rose water, lime or liquorice.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] A version of the dish, known as Kachang mera, was also sold during the 1930s.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] By the 1940s, the version of the dish described as having "shaved ice heaped into a little mountain", topped with red beans, "a Chinese grape-like fruit", syrup, and condensed or evaporated milk, similar to how it is being prepared today, began to appear.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] Some earlier variants of ais kacang are no longer sold, such as the ice ball version of the dessert, which was popular during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] In Malaysia, variants now contain a large serving of *attap chee* (palm seed), red beans, sweet corn, grass jelly, roasted peanuts, and cubes of agar agar as common ingredients.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] Other less common ingredients include aloe vera, *cendol*, *nata de coco*, and ice cream.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] A final topping of evaporated milk, condensed milk, or coconut milk is drizzled over the mountain of ice along with red rose syrup and sarsi syrup.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] Some stalls have even introduced novelty toppings such as durian and chocolate syrup.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] There are also versions that shun the multi-coloured syrup and are served instead with just a drizzling of palm sugar syrup.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] In Singapore, traditional ice kachang is usually made from shaved ice, packed into a mountain-like shape and consists of red beans, creamed corn, attap chee, cendol, and grass jelly, similar to the Malaysian version, and drizzled with syrups made from gula melaka, red rose syrup, and pandan syrup.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ais-kacang] The dish has evolved to include fruits such as durian, mango, toppings such as Milo, peanuts, and sago pearls among others.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] The dish is also prepared in Sakarya, Turkey among the Abaza people and is patented by the Turkish Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] In 2018, ajika was included on the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Georgia list.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] The word *ajika* comes from the Abkhaz language and means 'salt'.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] However, in the Mingrelian language, a sharp linguistic distinction is maintained: the native word for salt is **jim** (ჯიმჷ), while *ajika* (აჯიკა) refers exclusively to the spicy condiment.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] While the name is a Northwest Caucasian loanword, the dish is a defining staple of Mingrelian cuisine.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] In the Abkhaz language, the condiment is formally known as **apyrpyl-jika** (pepper-salt), whereas the standalone term *ajika* became the standardized name for the specific Mingrelian preparation.
[src:bambangan-condiment/ajika] This distinction confirms that in the Mingrelian tradition, Ajika is not a synonym for salt, but a unique, processed condiment.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] It is commonly paired with the raw fish salad dish of *hinava*, simmered fish of *pinaasakan sada* or also eaten with white rice, with flavours describes as a mix of tangy, sour, and sweet.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] Rich in vitamin C as well as an antioxidant agent with high levels of beta-carotene for the maintenance of eye and skin health, the *bambangan* condiment can last for a year with proper storage.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] Its main ingredient, the fruit, is also known for its very strong and pungent smell, similar to *durian*, especially when it is ripe, although the unpleasant smell will disappear once it is turned into the condiment.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The *bambangan* condiment has been a cultural heritage and inseparable part of the Kadazan-Dusun ethnics, where the *Mangifera pajang* tree has been growing in the wild of the indigenous homeland and cultivated by them through seed propagation.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The plant species from the *Anacardiaceae* family is widely found in the Borneo islands, especially Sabah where it has been part of the state food heritage.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The fruit can be found sold in almost every Sabah's weekend market (*tamu*) and vegetables market.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The condiment is prepared by washing fresh *bambangan* (*Mangifera pajang*) fruits, and the surface of the fruit needs to be wiped completely dry to prevent dirt attached to its skin from touching the inside of the fruit.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The skin will then peel thinly so as not to let one touch the inside part, with the outer layers being used in condiment making.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] It was then wiped until clean and cut into small cubes, with the inner seed part of the fruit also being taken, washed, and cut into small pieces or blended.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The inner seed part will then be mixed with the inside of the *bambangan* fruit with the addition of salt, with the ratio of salt to *bambangan* seeds being 2:1.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] All ingredients, including bird's eye chilli, will be mixed and stirred until smooth before being transferred into a jar or plastic container and filled until it becomes solid form, and the air or wind needs to exit when it is placed inside the container.
[src:bambangan-condiment/bambangan-condiment] The condiment mixture is left to ferment for around 7–10 days under room temperature in a tightly closed container.
